{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565854"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:33:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:33:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.12,0.33,0.34,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103245"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85663"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103245"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has no symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her thyroid is not palpable and there are no cervical lymph nodes. She requests thyroid cancer screening as she has read about the rising rates of thyroid cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the increased incidence of thyroid cancer over recent decades?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased dietary intake of iodine","Increased radiation in the atmosphere","Increased radiation use in diagnostic procedures","Increased use of ultrasound imaging","Increased incidence of obesity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe dramatic increase in thyroid cancer incidence (over 300% in the last four decades) without a corresponding increase in mortality suggests overdiagnosis rather than a true increase in disease burden. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased use of ultrasound imaging\u003C/strong\u003E has led to the detection of many small, indolent thyroid cancers that would likely never have caused clinical problems. This phenomenon is known as the \u0027thyroid cancer epidemic\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased dietary intake of iodine\u003C/strong\u003E has not been linked to the rising incidence of thyroid cancer. In fact, iodine deficiency is more commonly associated with thyroid disorders, including goitre and hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased radiation in the atmosphere\u003C/strong\u003E is not supported by environmental monitoring data. While radiation exposure is a known risk factor for thyroid cancer (particularly after nuclear accidents), there has not been a significant change in background radiation levels that would explain the observed increase in thyroid cancer cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased radiation use in diagnostic procedures\u003C/strong\u003E, while a theoretical concern, has not been shown to be the primary driver of increased thyroid cancer incidence. The dose from most diagnostic procedures is relatively low, and the temporal relationship doesn\u0027t match the observed increase in cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased incidence of obesity\u003C/strong\u003E has been associated with a modest increase in thyroid cancer risk, but the magnitude of this effect is far too small to explain the dramatic rise in thyroid cancer diagnoses. Additionally, the obesity epidemic timeline doesn\u0027t perfectly correlate with thyroid cancer incidence trends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend against routine screening for thyroid cancer in asymptomatic individuals. The risks of overdiagnosis and overtreatment (including unnecessary surgery and lifelong thyroid replacement therapy) outweigh the potential benefits in most cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The rising incidence of thyroid cancer is primarily due to increased detection of small, indolent cancers through widespread use of imaging.","Routine thyroid cancer screening in asymptomatic individuals is not recommended.","Despite the rising incidence of thyroid cancer, mortality rates have remained stable."],"references":["Chen DW, Lang BHH, McLeod DSA, et al. Thyroid cancer. Lancet 2023; 401: 1531\u201344","Boucai L, Zafereo M, Cabanillas ME. Thyroid Cancer A Review. JAMA 2024; 331:424-35."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85663"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85663"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-20T21:06:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-20T21:06:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103245"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt